<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLU HANDLES LA VERNE, GRABS SHARE OF TITLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN ORTEGA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 One down. One to go. 
</P>
<P>
 That was the feeling among Cal Lutheran players and coaches after the Kingsmen 
defeated La Verne, 103-90, in a Southern California Intercollegiate Athletic 
Conference men's basketball game Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
 The victory was the third in a row for Cal Lutheran (23-2, 12-2 in conference 
play) and gave the Kingsmen a share of their third consecutive SCIAC title. 
</P>
<P>
 It also set up a playoff game against co-champion Pomona Pitzer on Saturday 
night at Occidental to determine which team will gain the SCIAC's automatic 
entry in the NCAA Division III playoffs beginning next week. 
</P>
<P>
 It is the second year in a row that Cal Lutheran will play in a SCIAC playoff 
game. The Kingsmen lost to co-champion La Verne last season. 
</P>
<P>
 "Now we have a chance to decide it on the court," Cal Lutheran Coach Mike 
Dunlap said. "And I'm really looking forward to it." 
</P>
<P>
 Rupert Sapwell, who scored 25 points to go along with his eight rebounds, 
echoed Dunlap's sentiments. 
</P>
<P>
 "This was a real big game for us, but we want Pomona as bad as anyone," he 
said. "That will be a rumble on Saturday night." 
</P>
<P>
 The Kingsmen and Sagehens split their two meetings this season. Cal Lutheran 
won, 96-77, on Jan. 22, and Pomona scored an 85-76 victory in overtime last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
 "The guys are definitely looking forward to playing them again, but we knew we 
had to win this game tonight if we wanted a (conference title) banner," Dunlap 
said. "If we wanted a three-peat, we had to win tonight." 
</P>
<P>
 Cal Lutheran appeared to have the victory wrapped up with 6 1/2 minutes left 
when Dave Ulloa hit a pair of free throws to give the Kingsmen an 83-61 lead, 
but La Verne (12-12, 8-6) countered with a 14-3 run to trim the deficit to 
86-75. 
</P>
<P>
 Sapwell ended the Leopards' streak with a pair of free throws with 3:45 left 
and Cal Lutheran went on a 12-6 run of its own to take a 98-81 lead with 1:48 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
 "They weren't going to let us enjoy the win until after the game, that's for 
sure," Dunlap said. "We weren't playing badly on defense, but they were just on 
fire." 
</P>
<P>
 Led by Aaron Courseault (26 points) and Mark King (12), La Verne hit nine 
three-point shots in the second half.  
</P>
<P>
 During one stretch in which La Verne cut a 68-43 deficit to 76-61, all 18 of 
the Leopards' points came on three-point baskets by either Courseault or King. 
</P>
<P>
 Damon Ridley had 23 points, six rebounds and seven assists for Cal Lutheran 
and Derrick Clark added 17 points and nine rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
 Paul LaMott added 15 points and seven rebounds for the Kingsmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
