<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: OJAI; COUNCIL APPROVES CHILD-CARE PROGRAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An audience of dozens of parents cheered loudly after the Ojai City Council 
approved participating in a joint program with the local school district that 
would provide before- and after-school child care to needy children. 
</P>
<P>
 The plan, approved by council members sitting as the Redevelopment Agency, 
would offer day care to up to 35 schoolchildren inside a portable classroom 
that would be located on the Topa Topa Elementary School campus. 
</P>
<P>
 Under the agreement approved by the City Council late Tuesday, the city would 
use up to $28,000 in redevelopment funds to help get the project started. 
</P>
<P>
 The school district would provide the space for the classroom for $550 a 
month, but the operation of the facility would be administered by a local 
nonprofit group called Smart Start. 
</P>
<P>
 Speaker after speaker urged the council to approve the joint operating 
agreement, which had come under fire at previous public meetings. 
</P>
<P>
 No one spoke against the plan Tuesday night. But some day-care providers and 
others argued at earlier discussions that public agencies should not be 
supporting private agencies. 
</P>
<P>
 "We want to create a relaxed, trusting atmosphere," said Dana Huffman of Smart 
Start. "We want to provide affordable care during those times when children are 
not at school." 
</P>
<P>
 Child care would cost between $175 and $223 a month under the plan submitted 
by Huffman. JEFF McDONALD 
</P>
</TEXT>
