<HEADLINE>
<P>
MOVIE REVIEW; AN ACTION-PACKED 'CRIME STORY'; MARTIAL ARTS SUPERSTAR JACKIE 
CHAN CUTS THE CLOWNING WHEN HE SETS OUT TO RESCUE A KIDNAPED HONG KONG TYCOON. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEVIN THOMAS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 "Crime Story" (at the Monica 4-Plex), which is as fast and furious as action 
pictures get, provides a shrewd change of pace for martial arts superstar 
Jackie Chan. As skilled at comedy as he is at kung fu, Chan this time plays it 
straight as an inspector in the Royal Hong Kong Police. His seriousness proves 
to be an effective foil to this exceedingly sleek movie's spectacular stunt 
work and its visual panache. 
</P>
<P>
 Inspired by a 1991 incident, the film gets under way when a real estate tycoon 
(Law Ka-Ying), a past kidnap victim, senses that history is about to repeat 
itself. Sure enough, Law and his wife (Au Yeung Pui-Shan) are nabbed as they're 
driving on Hong Kong's convoluted Peak Road; it's the first of the film's many 
action set-pieces. Soon released, Law's wife receives a ransom demand of $60 
million for her husband's return. Chan is assigned to the case, partnered with 
a portly veteran cop (capable Kent Cheng). 
</P>
<P>
 Director Kirk Wong (plus an uncredited Chan) and a raft of writers and 
cameramen, plus crack editor Peter Cheung, combine all the details of an astute 
police procedural with one exciting sequence after another. There are chases 
galore, including one over Taipei roof tops and the rafters of a burlesque 
theater interspersed with contrasting images of Hong Kong's skyscraper canyons 
and congested back alleys. There's a terrific episode aboard a flooded ship, a 
classic rescue of a child from a burning tenement and a climactic scene set in 
a 7-Eleven on busy Waterloo Road. Movies don't get much more kinetic than 
"Crime Story," which is fun all the way. 
</P>
<P>
 'Crime Story' 
</P>
<P>
 Jackie Chan: Inspector Eddie Chan 
</P>
<P>
 Kent Cheng: Inspector Hung 
</P>
<P>
 Law Ka-Ying Wong: Yat-Fei. 
</P>
<P>
 Au Yeung Pui-Shan: Mrs. Wong 
</P>
<P>
 A Rim Films release of a Golden Harvest production. Director Kirk Wong. 
Producer Chua Lam. Screenplay Chun Tin-Nam, Cheung Chi-Sing, Llau Kar-Wei, Chu 
Wai-Kwong. Cinematographers Lau Wai-Keung, Lam Kwok-Wah, Poon Hang-Seng, Arthur 
Wong, Chan Kwong-Hung. Editor Peter Cheung. Costumes Chong Chi-Leung, Cheung 
Hok-Yun. Music James Wong. Production designer/art directors Tony Au, Lui 
Chor-Hung, Luk Chi-Fung. Sound Chow Siu-Lung. In Cantonese, with English and 
Chinese subtitles. Running time: 1 hour, 45 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
 MPAA rating: Unrated. Times guidelines: standard martial arts violence, some 
sexually suggestive scenes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
