<P>
MAN HELD IN SEXUAL ATTACKS ON 3 WOMEN; CRIME: SUSPECT IS ARRESTED AFTER VICTIMS 
REPORTED ASSAULTS NEAR ORANGE COAST COLLEGE IN COSTA MESA. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Costa Mesa man was arrested on suspicion of sexually attacking three women 
Thursday near Orange Coast College, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police said the three women, who reported the attacks within 20 minutes of 
each other, identified Matthew Paul Krieger, 21, as the suspect. 
</P>
<P>
 Krieger was arrested in the area and booked into the Costa Mesa Jail on 
suspicion of attempted rape. He was held on $50,000 bail, according to police 
Investigator George Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
 About 3:20 p.m., the first victim, a 21-year-old Orange Coast College student, 
told police a man approached her from behind while she was walking on Merrimac 
Way near the campus, grabbed her, tried to fondle her and made lewd remarks, 
Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
 The woman screamed and broke free from the assailant, who fled. 
</P>
<P>
 About 20 minutes later, a 27-year-old Costa Mesa woman reported that she was 
grabbed while walking with a 40-year-old Tustin woman in the 300 block of 
Hanover Drive, about two miles from the site of the first attack. 
</P>
<P>
 The younger woman screamed and got away from the attacker, who then accosted 
the older woman, knocked her to the ground and fondled her, Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
 The assailant fled when the two women's screams attracted residents. 
</P>
<P>
 Police found Krieger a short distance from the scene of the second attack. All 
the victims identified Krieger as the attacker, Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Investigators said that Krieger may have been involved in similar attacks, and 
asked anyone with information to contact Detective Frank Rudisill at (714) 
754-5363. 
</P>
